As coronavirus (covid-19) remains a global concern, the West African region is strategising to build epidemology capacity for outbreak response and bridge preparedness caps. This was made known on Thursday at a two-day simulation exercise to strengthen regional preparedness and readiness capacities to Covid-19 epidemic in West Africa, organised by WAHO Regional Centre for Surveillance & Disease Control (RCSDC) and sponsored by the Africa Union Centre for Disease Control (Africa CDC). Addressing journalists at the event, the regional coordinator, Nigeria and Anglophone West Africa, African Field Epidemology Network, Dr. Patrick Nguku, said the aim of the meeting is to understand the level of preparedness for member states. He said, obviously, there are gaps and the meeting hopes to identify specific gaps that member states, WAHO can address. According to him, “There are already existing gaps; our labs are not working, our surveillance system are not adequate, we don’t have enough personnels in the hospitals and there are no isolation centres. So there are gaps. “The ability to report case depend on the capability of the country. How is the surveillance system, human resources, clinical system and lab? It is relevant to determine what the gaps are in our preparedness. This is the time and i think the meeting will come up with specific gaps that member state will be ready to address.” In a presentation, the Africa CDC, informed that COVIDE-19 has an incubation period up to 14 days, with a mean incubation time of 5 to 6 days after exposure. 